The Tory MP was targeted because of his tough stance against paramilitary groups. Republicans believed that a victory for Margaret Thatcher's Conservatives would give them an excuse to step up their campaign against the continuing presence of British forces in Northern Ireland. 71 years ago (1951) The world's first computer designed for business and administration UNIVAC 1 was unveiled at the US Census Bureau. Capable of making simple calculations at high speed, in 1952 it was famously used to correctly predict Dwight Eisenhower's landslide presidential election victory. 32 years ago (1990) An estimated 200,000 protesters attended an anti-Poll Tax rally in central London, which turned violent as mounted police charged against demonstrators blocking Whitehall. Riots broke out with reports of looting and cars being overturned, while a building in Trafalgar Square caught fire. 